Business Context¶

Our company loses 10% to 15% of its customers each year to its competitors. Even though we can't realistically keep all of its customers, devoting time to the customers who are more likely to leave is key to customer retention. In fact, keeping customers is much more feasible than acquiring new customers. For this purpose, as the data scientist of this company, I will build a deep learning pipeline to predict which customers are more likely to leave, so that we can put more effort into those cusomers.

The dataset was downloaded from the following link on kaggle:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/blastchar/telco-customer-churn

6. Feature Engineering¶

In [14]:
df_train['Churn'] = df_train['Churn'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
df_test['Churn'] = df_test['Churn'].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})

X_train = df_train.drop('Churn', axis = 1)
y_train = df_train['Churn']
X_test  = df_test.drop('Churn', axis = 1)
y_test = df_test['Churn']
In [15]:
categorical_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
numerical_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).columns

column_transformer = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [('cat', OneHotEncoder(),categorical_cols),
                    ('num', MinMaxScaler(), numerical_cols)
                    ])

column_transformer.fit(X_train)
X_train_encoded = column_transformer.transform(X_train)
X_test_encoded = column_transformer.transform(X_test)

cat_features = column_transformer.transformers_[0][1].get_feature_names_out(categorical_cols)
num_features = column_transformer.transformers_[1][2]
all_features = list(cat_features) + list(num_features)

X_train = pd.DataFrame(X_train_encoded, columns=all_features)
X_test = pd.DataFrame(X_test_encoded, columns=all_features)

7. Feature Selection using decision trees¶

In [16]:
grid_parameters = {"criterion": ["gini", "entropy"],
             "min_samples_split": [10, 20, 40],
             "max_depth": [2,3,4],
             "min_samples_leaf": [100, 40, 20, 1],
             "max_leaf_nodes": [20,10,5]}

clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight = 'balanced')
grid = GridSearchCV(clf, grid_parameters,scoring = 'f1', cv=10)
search=grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_tree = search.best_estimator_
best_score = search.best_score_

print( "Best f1 score:", round(best_score * 100, 1), '%')
print( "Optimal hyperparameters:")
print(search.best_params_)

8 Computational experimentation¶

In this section we split the dataset into training and validation sets, we run the model using different hyperparameters and we choose the best parameters on the test set tom make our predictions. We use f1-score for the class Y = 1 as our evaluation metric, as we are more interested in finding customers who are at more risk of churning

9. Final Model¶

In [22]:
class_weights = compute_class_weight(class_weight='balanced', classes=np.unique(y_train), y=y_train)
class_weights_dict = dict(enumerate(class_weights))

model = Sequential([
Dense(45, input_shape = (38,), activation = 'linear'),
#Dense(1, activation = 'tanh'),
Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid')
    ])
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy')
start_time = time.time()
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 10, batch_size = 64, validation_data = (X_val, y_val), class_weight=class_weights_dict )
y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
y_test_pred = np.where(y_test_pred > 0.5, 1, 0)

end_time = time.time()
execution_time = end_time - start_time

print('Classification report: ')
print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
print('Execution time: ', execution_time)

10. Summary of the results¶

This pipeline aims to work on the f1-score for the class y = 1. Configuration 6 had the best performance, with a test set f1-score of 63% and an execution time of 3.76s. We notice that the contract duration is the most important feature to predict customer churn and the shorter the contract, the more likely the customer is to leave. Implementing this pipeline enables the company to detect 63% of customers who are more likely to chur. Thus, the company makes more marketing efforts towards those customers and saves its market share.

11. Limitations:¶

Although the pipeline is strong overall, we cannot optimize for all the metrics at once and we can only make some tradeoffs to make a pipeline that can make some improvement to the business. In addition, the imbalanced nature of the dataset makes it harder to perform equally well on both classes. Furthermore, even though we have a strong performance, the model is harder to interpret because of the use of neural networks.
